

{ No datatypes necessary

code {
create table table_abc (col_1, col_2, col_3);

insert into table_abc values ('foo', 'bar', 'baz');
insert into table_abc values (   1 ,   42 ,   20 );

select * from table_abc;
code }

  Although no datatypes are necessary when the table is created, the behaviour can be influenced: `integer primary key autoincrement` etc.

  See also → development/databases/SQLite/functions/typeof.

}
{ Tabular output

code {
sqlite3> .mode column
sqlite3> .width 10 25 54 …
sqlite3> select foo, bar, baz, … from tData;
code }

}
{ Turning off autocommit

  SQLLite commits every statement by default (so called *auto commit*).

  To turn this behaviour off (which increases performance greatly when lots of statements are executed in sequence), the statements must be enclosed in `begin transaction` .. `commit transaction`:
code {
begin transaction;

insert into tab_something values ('foo', 'bar', 'baz');
insert into tab_something values ('one', 'two',  null);
…
…

commit transaction;
code }

}
{ pragma

code {
pragma quick_check;
code }

}
{ PHP

  It seems sqlite can be accessed (in Ubuntu) from → development/web/php with
code {
sudo apt-get install php-sqlite3
code }

